UDJE 1: A
Abaka riẹ ẹbe rẹ enẹ mẹ na.
EXAMPLE 1: Grashopper ate my yam's leaves.
UDJE 2: Ya jẹ abaka na vwo; wo hwe-e.
EXAMPLE 2: Leave the grahopper alone; do not kill it.

TRANSLATION: rag, piece of cloth, torn  piece  of  cloth
UDJE 1: Abamwa yẹ oku phiyọ rhe etinẹ.
EXAMPLE 1: It was rag he/she down here.
UDJE 2: Biko kẹ vwẹ abamwa mi vwo ririẹ imẹdjẹ na.
EXAMPLE 2: Please give me a piece of cloth to clean the table

UDJE 1: Ovwa ghare emu na abavo.
EXAMPLE 1: Share the food (or thing) equally.
UDJE 2: Abavo ọ yẹ oguẹdjọ na brẹ orhiẹ na.
EXAMPLE 2: The judge gave a fair judgement.

TRANSLATION: A species of water yam with red colored leaves and tuber
UDJE 1: Abe na nabọ vwerhe.
EXAMPLE 1: The abe tastes well.
UDJE 2: Me kẹ abe phi yẹ udju mẹ.
EXAMPLE 2: I planted abe in my farm.

UDJE 1: Nighere, e brẹ orhiẹ hwe we; wọ riẹ abe՛.
EXAMPLE 1: Look, the verdict is against you; you are guilty
UDJE 2: Me riẹ abe՛ rẹ ota nana-a.
EXAMPLE 2: I am not guilty in this matter.

UDJE 1: E jẹ a vwẹ abémuó vwo vughẹ ohwo rẹ ọma goma.
EXAMPLE 1: Let us use wrestling to determine the strongest person.
UDJE 2: Avwaren kpẹ abémuó vwẹ obẹ ọgua rẹ ọkaorho.
EXAMPLE 2: We are going for a wrestling at the chief's court.

UDJE 1: Inogbozighi chẹ abẹrẹn rẹ ovie na nẹ ọgua rọye.
EXAMPLE 1: Hooligans have stolen the king's royal sword from his palace.
UDJE 2: Ọsẹ mẹ rode ọye ri dẹ abẹrẹn na miẹ ọneki oyibo re se Winterson.
EXAMPLE 2: It was my grand father who bought the royal sword from a white trader called Winterson.

UDJE 1: Abérha yẹ ọkpako nyẹ ota.
EXAMPLE 1: It is thrice an elder hears an utterance.
UDJE 2: Aberha Otiti riẹ emu odẹye.
EXAMPLE 2: Otiti ate thrice yesterday.

UDJE 1: Ọna ọvwọ gba abivẹ oravwọ nana phiare.
EXAMPLE 1: This made twice this thing has happened.
UDJE 2: Jẹ o ruo abivẹ tavwe wo ki ruo keri.
EXAMPLE 2: Let him/her do it twice before you retalliate.

UDJE 1: Mọ e mu abọ.
EXAMPLE 1: Come let's wrestle.
UDJE 2: Abọ emuo yoma mamọ.
EXAMPLE 2: Wrestling is very good.

UDJE 1: Riẹ abọ wẹ kẹ vwẹ.
EXAMPLE 1: Stretch your hands towards me.
UDJE 2: Ra a hworhẹ abọ wẹ.
EXAMPLE 2: Go and wash your hands.

UDJE 1: Mi se we abọ iyorin, wọ kpare kẹ vwẹ-ẹ
EXAMPLE 1: I called you five times, you didn't answer me.
UDJE 2: Wo ruẹ emu nana abọ buebu re.
EXAMPLE 2: You have done this many times.

UDJE 1: Mi se we abọ nonẹ nu wo ru obo ri fori ọke eje.
EXAMPLE 1: I challenge (encourage) you today to do what is right all the time.
UDJE 2: Vwẹ ọna vwo se aye abọ.
EXAMPLE 2: Challenge/encourage them with this.

UDJE 1: Abotu aye vwo muo yara.
EXAMPLE 1: They carried him/her/it away with group effort.
UDJE 2: We biko, e jẹ a vwẹ abotu vwọ wian owian na.
EXAMPLE 2: Please let us use group effort  to do the job.

UDJE 1: Oniovo mẹ kpẹ ada.
EXAMPLE 1: My sibling went on outing.
UDJE 2: Wo kpẹ ada nọ.
EXAMPLE 2: You go on outing too much.

UDJE 1: Nya vwẹ áda kẹ vwẹ me vwọ chẹ idjighere mẹ.
EXAMPLE 1: Cut me a forked stick to wedge my bicycle.
UDJE 2: Áda wọ nya vwe kẹ vwẹ na gare-e.
EXAMPLE 2: The forked stick you cut for me is not strong.

TRANSLATION: when (as in when something is being done)
UDJE 1: Ihwo suẹ une nana ádá vwẹ ọmọtẹ kpẹ orọvwe
EXAMPLE 1: People sing this song when a girl is given out in marriage.
UDJE 2: Ádá riẹ emu a tẹ ota-a.
EXAMPLE 2: One does not talk when eating.

UDJE 1: Ọbo na muẹ izobo kpẹ adérha.
EXAMPLE 1: The native doctor took the sacrifice to a three-way junction.
UDJE 2: Hẹrhẹ ovwẹ wo de tẹ adérha na.
EXAMPLE 2: Wait on me when you get to the three-way junction.

UDJE 1: Mu adján na ke vwe.
EXAMPLE 1: Help me catch the bat.
UDJE 2: Adján na rha kpo.
EXAMPLE 2: The bat escaped.

TRANSLATION: chain of coral beads worn round the neck by chiefs
‘hamster’ [B. there are no hamsters in Nigeria. Perhaps a bush-rat?]
Urhobo name for the Edo (Bini) people and their language
metal trap used for catching small animals such as rats
very flat bead made from rubber or palm kernel shells
charm for protection against the dead
exclamation of disbelief, shock or surprise, also used for questioning.
UDJE 1: Án, idie wọ ta na?
EXAMPLE 1: Án, what are you saying?
UDJE 2: Án, a ji mrẹ emu etiẹ ọna?
EXAMPLE 2: Án, does one see things such as this?

TRANSLATION: lower wrapper (of the two) worn by women
old coin, originally a tenth of a penny
special bead worn on the neck like a bow-tie by traditional rulers
charm for protection against any poisonous thing taken in by mouth
designated spot where traditional rites are offered to the ancestors
bird with red beak that bores hole in the pit
tray, flat basin (made locally from a plant called éti)
wide area with collection of ponds
charm for postponing evil days such as death
wife always treated with disdain by the husband
Urhobo name for the Hausa people and their language
basket used by women in fishing
exp meet you well (i.e. at table)
spirit roaming in the forest which gives rise to whirlwind
be loose (of a baby carried on the back)
v.t thank, general greeting which expresses variety of sentiments
